05317nam a22007815i 9781501705915DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979581330  a97815017059157 a10.7591/97815017059152doi  a(DE-B1597)478717  a(OCoLC)956482282  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR658.R43bB76 2017 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a822.3093578223  aHI 12542rvk0(DE-625)rvk/49810:1 aBrokaw, Katherine Steele, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStaging Harmony :bMusic and Religious Change in Late Medieval and Early Modern English Drama /cKatherine Steele Brokaw. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on the Text -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Theater, Music, and Religion in the Long Sixteenth Century -- tChapter 1. Sacred, Sensual, and Social Music: Wisdom and the Digby Mary Magdalene -- tChapter 2. Musical Hypocrisy: The Plays of John Bale -- tChapter 3. Learning to Sing: The Plays of Nicholas Udall -- tChapter 4. Propaganda and Psalms: Early Elizabethan Drama -- tChapter 5. Sound Effects: Doctor Faustus -- tChapter 6. Arts to Enchant: The Tempest and The Winter’s Tale -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Staging Harmony, Katherine Steele Brokaw reveals how the relationship between drama, music, and religious change across England's long sixteenth century moved religious discourse to more moderate positions. It did so by reproducing the complex personal attachments, nostalgic overtones, and bodily effects that allow performed music to evoke the feeling, if not always the reality, of social harmony. Brokaw demonstrates how theatrical music from the late fifteenth to the early seventeenth centuries contributed to contemporary discourses on the power and morality of music and its proper role in religious life, shaping the changes made to church music as well as people’s reception of those changes. In representing social, affective, and religious life in all its intricacy, and in unifying auditors in shared acoustic experiences, staged musical moments suggested the value of complexity, resolution, and compromise rather than oversimplified, absolutist binaries worth killing or dying for.The theater represented the music of the church’s present and past. By bringing medieval and early Tudor drama into conversation with Elizabethan and Jacobean drama, Brokaw uncovers connections and continuities across diverse dramatic forms and demonstrates the staying power of musical performance traditions. In analyzing musical practices and discourses, theological debates, devotional practices, and early staging conditions, Brokaw offers new readings of well-known plays (Marlowe’s Doctor Faustus, Shakespeare’s The Tempest and The Winter’s Tale) as well as Tudor dramas by playwrights including John Bale, Nicholas Udall, and William Wager.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDramatic musiczEnglandy16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aReligion and dramaxHistoryy16th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aPerforming Arts & Drama. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2